SUB-TASK 1: Render markdown tables in chat bubbles
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Backend already returns markdown tables for several outputs:
- "show my tasks" (RMS reviewer)
- "show pending approvals" (RMS approver, MRR approver)
- Bulk Excel summaries

Example markdown sent by backend:

    ### Your Assigned Tasks

    | Task ID | Project | Product | Task Idx | Start | End | Planned Hrs |
    |---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
    | 22 | 100 | 10 | 1 | 2026-05-26 | 2026-05-28 | 8 |
    | 23 | 100 | 10 | 2 | 2026-05-29 | 2026-06-02 | 6 |

    To log hours: log 8 hours on task <Task ID> for <YYYY-MM-DD> with remark "your note"

REQUIREMENT
Render markdown content in assistant chat bubbles using a markdown
renderer (e.g., react-markdown with remark-gfm for table support).

- Tables should render as actual HTML tables with proper borders,
  alternating row colors, and good readability.
- Headers (### H3) should render as styled headings.
- Bold (**text**) and inline code (`code`) should style correctly.
- Lists (- bullet) render as bullets.

Suggested library: react-markdown + remark-gfm
    npm install react-markdown remark-gfm

Make sure tables don't overflow on mobile — horizontal scroll or
responsive collapse is acceptable.

User chat bubbles (the ones the USER sends) stay as plain text.
Only ASSISTANT chat bubbles get markdown rendering.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SUB-TASK 2: Render form widgets emitted by backend
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Backend will emit a special chunk for form widgets. Format:

    data: {"type": "form_widget", "form": <FORM_JSON>}

where FORM_JSON conforms to this contract:

{
    "form_id": "mrr_create_form",
    "title": "Create Material Requisition",
    "description": "Fill in the details below and click Submit.",
    "submit_label": "Submit MRR",
    "cancel_label": "Cancel",
    "fields": [
        {
            "name": "project_id",
            "label": "Project ID",
            "type": "text",
            "required": true,
            "placeholder": "e.g. 100"
        },
        {
            "name": "phase_id",
            "label": "Phase",
            "type": "select",
            "required": true,
            "options": [
                {"value": "DESIGN", "label": "Design"},
                {"value": "BUILD", "label": "Build"},
                {"value": "TEST", "label": "Test"}
            ]
        },
        {
            "name": "need_by_date",
            "label": "Need By Date",
            "type": "date",
            "required": true
        },
        {
            "name": "remarks",
            "label": "Remarks",
            "type": "textarea",
            "required": false,
            "rows": 3
        },
        {
            "name": "items",
            "label": "Items",
            "type": "items_table",
            "required": true,
            "min_rows": 1,
            "columns": [
                {"name": "item_code", "label": "Item Code", "type": "text"},
                {"name": "qty", "label": "Quantity", "type": "number"}
            ]
        }
    ]
}

SUPPORTED FIELD TYPES
- text: single-line input
- number: numeric input (with min/max if specified)
- date: date picker (YYYY-MM-DD format)
- textarea: multi-line input
- select: dropdown with options array
- checkbox: boolean toggle
- items_table: a repeating row table (user can add/remove rows); each
  row has the fields defined in "columns". Always show a "+ Add row"
  button below the table.

REQUIREMENT
- Render the form INLINE in the chat (or in a modal — your call,
  inline preferred for chat flow).
- On Submit click:
    - Collect all field values into a JSON object.
    - For items_table fields, collect rows as an array of objects.
    - Post to the SAME chat endpoint as a regular message, but the
      message body should be:
          {"action": "form_submit", "form_id": "<form_id>",
           "data": <collected_field_values>}
    - Send this as the user's "message" in the next request.
- On Cancel click:
    - Send "cancel" as a plain text message.
- Show validation errors inline (required fields, number ranges).

EXAMPLE submit payload posted to backend:

    {
        "action": "form_submit",
        "form_id": "mrr_create_form",
        "data": {
            "project_id": "100",
            "phase_id": "DESIGN",
            "need_by_date": "2026-06-15",
            "remarks": "urgent",
            "items": [
                {"item_code": "04617", "qty": 5},
                {"item_code": "04618", "qty": 2}
            ]
        }
    }

Backend will receive this as the user message, parse the JSON,
validate, and process. Same single-submit pattern as Excel upload.

NOTE: This is single-screen / single-submit. NOT a wizard.

You can stub the backend behaviour during development by sending a
hardcoded form_widget event from a mock — the contract above is
what the real backend will send.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SUB-TASK 3: Capture and resend thread_id
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Backend already sends a `meta` event at the start of every streaming
response:

    data: {"type": "meta", "thread_id": "9534eafd-f55f-4915-8510-..."}

CURRENT BEHAVIOR
Frontend likely sends thread_id=None on every request, so each turn
starts fresh. Verified in backend logs:
    [DIAG-CONTROLLER] thread_id received: None

REQUIREMENT
- Capture the thread_id from the meta event of the FIRST response in
  a conversation.
- Store it (in component state, conversation object — whatever fits
  the app's structure).
- Send it back as `thread_id` in every subsequent request body for
  that same conversation.
- On "new chat" / starting a fresh conversation, clear the stored
  thread_id so backend starts a new thread.

This unlocks multi-turn workflows (confirm/cancel, wizard forms)
later, and is harmless now (backend accepts and ignores until
checkpointer is wired). Costs nothing to add now, costs a lot to
retrofit later.

